Another piece of internal evidence, of a more positive kind, bearing upon the question of the date of the manuscript, as well as upon that of the place where it was written, is to be found at p. 368, where at the bottom of the page there appear in red uncial letters the words ‘Memento Domine famuli tui Remedii Episcopi! The purpose of the insertion has evidently been that Remedius should be mentioned by name in the ‘Memento vivorum'r and it is at least a most probable conjecture that the Remedius thus referred to is the great Bishop Remedius of Chur.. The inference that the Sacramentary belonged to Re· medius himself 1fs perhaps hardly warrantede but it seems clear that it must have been written during the life of Reme· dius, and in some place where bis name would receive such a special mention.

This mention is given to him, apparently, not as the Bishop of the diocese, since the Canon Actionis also contains the words ‘et antistite nostro Ill.,' and it seems most likely that its pre· sence is due to the peculiar position of Remedius as a tempor-al prince. The see of Chur, in the seventb and eighth centuries, was hereditary in the family known as the Victoridae. The Bishops exercised temporal as well as spiritual authority in the district known as ‘Rhaetia Curiensis' (an entirely un·Teut0nized district, the boundaries of which nearly corresponded with those of the diocese), and bore the title of ‘Praenes' The last of the Victoridae, Bishop Tello, died about 773, and his suc· censor in the see, Constantius, received probably in that year, from Charias the Great‚ the title and powers of ‘ Rector⁸.’ The purpose of Charles in this grant was no doubt to secure bis power in a district which bad as yet remained‚ by reason of its isolated situation, practically untouched by Teutonis colonists.
